message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The region of the stomach being incised is supplied by the right gastroepiploic artery. The short gastric arteries supply the fundus and the body of the stomach. The splenic artery supplies the fundus and the greater curvature. The right gastric artery supplies the lesser curvature.

The right half of the greater curvature of the stomach is supplied by the right gastroepiploic artery, which is a branch of the gastroduodenal artery. The short gastric arteries supply the fundus, the splenic artery supplies the left half of the greater curvature, and the right gastric artery supplies the lesser curvature of the stomach.

We refer to anatomy textbooks for help. The right gastroepiploic artery runs adjacent to the greater curvature of the stomach and directly supplies blood to this region. The short gastric arteries supply the fundus and the upper portion of the greater curvature. The splenic artery provides blood to the stomach but does not directly supply this region. The right gastric artery supplies the lesser curvature of the stomach.
